result.execSummary:
The defendant Austin M Franke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Manufacture/Deliver Non-Narcotics, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Submit to an AODA assessment, follow through with any treatment recommended.  No use or possession of illegal controlled substances or drug paraphernalia. Comply with random urine screens. Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent.

  If Probation/Extended Supervision is revoked and/or a prison term ordered, outstanding financial obligations shall be collected pursuant to statutory provisions, including deductions from inmate prison monies.  If discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and government entities for outstanding financial obligations.  Collections may include income assignment.

Expunction is conditionally granted upon verification of completion of sentence, payment of all costs/fees and no new criminal law violations.  Defendant must Petition the Court in writing upon successful completion of the sentence.

Defendant Austin M Franke in court, in custody, with attorney Kirk Andrew Redetzke.    District Attorney's Office Law Intern appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Court makes record of previous plea and sentencing and that the defendant had consumed controlled substances before that plea and sentencing hearing.  New Plea entered to count #1 of guilty.  Court finds the defendant guilty of Count #1.  Counts 2,3, and 4 are dismissed and read in.  State makes recommendations.  Attorney Redetzke makes statements.  Court wanted to make a record of the plea while the defendant was sober.  

The Court Orders the Following:  Count #1.  (ORIGINAL SENTENCE PREVIOUSLY ORDERD ON 5/2/2016.  COURT DOES NOT GO OVER WHOLE SENTENCE AGAIN, BUT THIS SENTENCE STANDS.)  

Imposed and Stayed Sentence of:

36 Months Imprisonment (Credit - 11 days )
18 months of Initial Confinement
18 months of Extended Supervision

Term of Probation: 3 Years
Early termination after 2 years if approved by agent
Conditions of Probation:
Follow through with any treatment and/or counseling recommended by Agent;	
AODA Assessment and follow through with any treatment recommended;
Absolute Sobriety; Random U.A.s;
No Use or Possession of illegal controlled substances or drug paraphernalia;
Inform agent of all prescriptions;
Disclose to any physician conditions of probation
Get all prescriptions from the same pharmacy
Seek / Maintain employment or GED;

Condition Time: 120 days, first 60 days without work release, last 60 days Huber with NON WORKING HOURS WITH STANDARD RELEASE CONDITIONS - To commence forthwith.  After 120 days, defendant to attend 90 days in day report center consecutive to the 120 days.  

Buy Money:  $220.00
COSTS:  $268.00
DNA Surcharge: $250.00
DNA Sample ordered and to be provided immediately if in custody or within (3) business days at the Waukesha County Sheriff Department. 
BAIL TO BE APPLIED.  

Defendant is eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program
Defendant is eligible for the Substance Abuse Program
Felony warnings, immigration warnings, voting rights and firearms warnings given.  
Expunction is conditionally granted upon completion of sentence, payment of all costs/fees and no new criminal law violations.  Defendant must Petition the Court in writing upon successful completion of the sentence.
